- ## Verification
#Verification #Verification  #Testing #ResearchStreams #AI #Engineering 
(5) Difficult to evaluate robustness against adversarial at- tacks on ML-based systems (safety meets security): In the last few years, many researchers have expressed their concerns about the potential threats to the stability of ML-based systems posed by adversarial attacks. It is difficult to predict such attacks, and it is also complicated to model the response of a component or system as a whole to such attacks. There- fore, to develop a reliable system it is imperative to not only analyze the inherent risks of ML-techniques, but also to protect them from intentional adversarial attacks. To ensure functional integrity of modern ML-based systems safety and security related knowledge should be used in combination. Szegedy et al. Biggio et al. first paid attention to adversarial examples that can eas- ily deceive neural networks (Szegedy et al., 2013; Biggio et al., 2013). If the attacker adds a small perturbation to an image with the proper calculation, a well-trained neural network (NN) can misclassify the image with surprisingly high confidence. Such unstable behavior can lead to catastrophic consequences in case of safety-critical systems that depend heavily on computer vision to take decisions. Numerous recent works have analyzed different ways to fool deep neural networks (DNN) (Nguyen et al., 2015; Papernot et al., 2017; Grosse et al., 2016; Papernot et al., 2016). Bastani et al. proposed metrics to measure robustness against such adversarial examples (Bastani et al., 2016). Very recently, Naseer et al. proposed formal methods to analyze noise tolerance, training bias, and input sensitivity of neural networks (Naseer et al., 2020). Similarly, RL agents can also be heavily manipulated by malicious attacks. Huang et al. (2017b) have recently shown that RL-algorithms such as DWN, TRPO, A3C can be vulnerable to malicious inputs. Even a small perturbation can lure an RL agent to move to an undesirable state and take unsafe action. White and black-box attacks have been well investigated in this work. In case of white-box attacks, the attacker is assumed to have access to the policy network. Whereas, black-box attacker have only partial or no such information. The researchers show that white-box attackers are more effective than black-box attackers. It is possible to confuse an RL agent with trained policy even in real-world black-box scenario. For instance, lane following policy of an autonomous car can be deliberately altered by placing a small mark on the road surface or road signs. Defenses against adversarial attacks: Various defense mechanisms have been proposed to ensure robustness of ML models. We briefly consider the two most discussed defense mechanisms. (i) Adversarial training: This is a brute force process of generating as many adver- sarial examples as possible and using them to train the model in advance. Since Szegedy et al. (2013) showed the existence of adversarial examples to fool DNNs, many researchers focused on ensuring robustness of learning models from such adversar- ial attacks (Papernot et al., 2017; Gu and Rigazio, 2014; Sha- ham et al., 2015). As discussed by Hazan et al., dealing with adversarial perturbation can eventually help to optimize a ML model in a more robust way (Hazan et al., 2017). One of the major challenges faced in training DNNs with adversarial exam- ples is synthesizing a sizable number of adversarial examples. Various ways have been proposed to synthesize such examples in whitebox settings (Moosavi-Dezfooli et al., 2016; Goodfellow et al., 2014; Szegedy et al., 2013; Papernot et al., 2017; Carlini and Wagner, 2017; Chen et al., 2017). Another challenge is to generate physical-world adversarial examples (2D photos, ad- versarial patches, 3D prints, etc.). These physical or real-world adversarial examples have been demonstrated for various do- mains such as face recognition, image classification, speech-to- text, etc. (Kurakin et al., 2016; Carlini et al., 2016; Eykholt et al., 2018). (ii) Defensive distillation: In this defense mechanism, a model is trained to provide out- puts in terms of probability instead of hard labels. The distillation process reduces the gradients used to create the adversarial ex- ample. As a result, this defensive mechanism of a DNN can reduce the effectiveness of adversarial sample from 95% to less than 0.5%. Detailed analysis of the state-of-the-art defensive measures can be found in recent surveys on robust deep learning (Ozdag, 2018; Chakraborty et al., 2018; Xu et al., 2020).

- ## ML
#ML #Workflow #Machine #Learning #ResearchStreams #AI #Engineering 
Machine learning workflow describes the overall develop- ment stages and activities that are typically performed when developing ML based software systems. At high-level, a ML workflow includes a set of distinguishable stages (see Figure 1): model requirements, data collection, data cleaning, data labelling, feature engineering, model training, model evalua- tion, model deployment and model monitoring [4]5 . These stages can be grouped in separate processes: (i) Data management, (ii) ML Modeling, and (iii) Model Operation. Data Management process includes collection of data and its preparation for its seamless usage. The Data Management process can be performed separately from ML modeling - very often data exists in enterprise repositories or as open repos- itories, and they offer usage for different ML applications. 5We define ML model as a ML function, or a ML component that will be developed and deployed in a software system. The ML modeling process corresponds to the development of a software component, or possibly a simple application - i.e. creation of ML model itself, adjusting data, training, and finally evaluating the model. This process is highly iterative and driven by the results, such as the accuracy of the model, the precision, or other quality attributes used during ML model training. The deployment and monitoring of the trained ML model belong to the operation process - integration of the ML model in the software system and its performance. Monitoring of ML component is seen as an integral part of a ML workflow that is useful in providing feedback to ML modelling, which may lead to a request for model re-training with new data sets, or a redesign of the model itself with new features and new model architectures. In practice, the development of ML systems is challenging for a variety of reasons [1], [5], [6]. Data that is used to build ML models has numerous data quality problems and requires huge efforts to prepare the data before training the models because often it can not be readily fed into ML algorithms [7]. Furthermore, manual and ad-hoc procedures in ML modelling stage make it difficult to reproduce model experimentation results and reduces the rate of experimentation, including tuning that can be done to improve the model [8], [9]. Despite its development challenges, ML model constitute a small part of the entire ML system [1], [6]. Once data scientists select the final ML model, it needs to be deployed and integrated to the end-user application. For complex sys- tems, the integration and deployment of ML models need to take into consideration numerous requirements related to the software system. The ML-based application also needs continuous monitoring in order to detect errors in predictions and data (e.g., training-serving skew) requiring that the ML model be retrained due to staleness.

Non- functional requirements related to different types of quality attributes are in many domains the main concern of the development process. Example of these are attributes related to dependability (safety, security, reliability, robustness, etc.), or resources (real-time requirements, performance, energy consumption, computational and storage constraints), or user interface (usability). The requirements related to ML workflow are different: data quality, data management effectiveness (data preparation, labeling), effectiveness of the training process (CPU training time), and resources needed in the training process. In relation to the quality of the ML models, there is a set of metrics that show the quality of the prediction: accuracy, precision and recall are some of them6 . In feature engineering, the requirements are related a the quality and effectiveness of feature selection and their processing (normalisation, transfor- mations, etc.) in relation to the prediction quality. In an integrated process, the main challenges lie in under- standing the relations between software system requirements and ML requirements.

This paper points out the challenges in development of complex systems that include ML components, and discuss possible solutions driven by the combination of DevOps and ML workflow processes. Industrial cases are presented to illustrate these challenges and the possible solutions.

#DevOps #Integration #Software #Engineering #ResearchStreams #AI #Engineering 
DM. Data management stage establishes activities and systems to collect data, select data, augment labelling and curate features that will be used for training ML models. Standardized activities and systems are put in place to help extract and store data in optimized formats that are easy and ready to be consumed by ML modelling stage, while also enforcing suitable security controls for accessing the data. The resulting data set building code creates connectors to raw data storage in order to select and extract samples of data from them. In Case A, all email communication data between sales representatives and prospects is stored in communication database from which a few data samples are selected and labelled. However, the extraction involves a series of steps to handle different encoding in order to get email text, extract entities and construct relationship around the entities. In Case B, a data ingestion service is implemented to build data set by extracting data from a large data collection storage containing log files and log analysis (performed by an external tool).

#DevOps #Integration #Software #Engineering #ResearchStreams #AI #Engineering 
Mod. Once new data set is made available for training at ML modelling stage, training environment is provisioned to facilitate model training and evaluation. ML model experiments can be carried out on ML platform, developed either internally or acquired as open-source tools, that provides the capability of analysing data sets and training ML models. At the stage information of each ML model experiment run i.e., datasets, trained model (including model configurations) and evaluation results are stored for easy comparison against a historical baseline e.g., a model that is currently in production. To facilitate tracking of artifact dependencies after a successful completion of ML model experiment, developers explicitly specify and register artifacts and their dependencies (data set, model and code) to a dependency tracking system that stores the experiment run history in a database. For each artifact, the developers specify its metadata (name, version number, registration date) and dependency information, which contain references to other elements that the artifacts depend on. For example, data set dependency information can be (i) data source e.g., log IDs, (ii) Git hash of the code used to extract data set from raw data, (iii) versioned set of data labels and (iv) entry point to extraction scripts etc [12]. Important to storing artifacts and their dependency information is that it should allow immutability i.e., it should be possible to recreate/reproduce the exact same artifact every time. The versioned artifacts and their dependency information is made accessible externally by other systems e.g., by build system through simple API calls. By the end of model experiment stage, the final trained model is selected and verified that it works correctly but in isolation from other ML components. Case A uses an externally developed AI platform to build and deploy models called Databricks With the tool, Case A stores the whole pipeline of conducting ML model experiment steps as a single archive file and the resulting models in a versioned controlled repository. In Case B, the ML modelling stage involves manual steps of data exploration, model training and evaluation. Developers implement and version model training code after successfully training a model. The model along with metadata information (name, version, classifier, features) is also stored in model registry.

Dev. When deploying the trained model, first it is verified that it operates correctly with the rest of the system i.e., other components. The build system performs system wide integration and verification over large test set to give holistic view of how all parts of the system performs between the different components. Additionally, since artifact dependency information and capability is accessible to build systems, such as the versioning and storing artifacts using code (data set generation code, model training code, evaluation metrics generation code), the build system can be implemented in such a way that it has the functionality to orchestrate and run the entire model training job on a regular basis. In case of the latter, the retraining models is automated and process is designated as failed, aborted or successful by the build. Successful build with best model - new model performs better than production model - is registered in model registry. In case of failed and aborted builds, developers can opt to rebuild the model with an optimized set of parameters. Historical builds executed by the CI system can be used to also identify and analyse bugs that occur in other components as a result of model updates. At the end, the verified latest registered version of a trained model is released/promoted to the subsequent quality assurance acceptance environment or the production environment only after successful build, including passing of regular integration and system tests. The regular tests include testing the AI component with different inputs to ensure appropriate response. In case A, one can reproduce the trained models by re-running the single archive file containing the whole model pipeline steps generated by Databricks tools. At the time of our study, both Case A and Case B were in the process of implementing tests. Case B was also planning to incorporate a CI system in order to help deal with technical debt that was accumulating due to time pressures requiring the team to delivery the system fast to the stakeholder. For example, unit tests were being implemented to help catch issues caused by the data ingestion service.

Ops. Once the ML system component is operational in pro- duction environment, including the trained model, the system is continuously monitored to detect issues like performance degradation. Deployment to the production environment can be a manual, semi-automated or automated process that is performed after successful execution of tests in pre-production environments in development step. The Ops stage also ensures live testing of AI component by providing predictions whilst adhering to stringent latency requirement. At this step, devel- opers also collect information of how the model is performing based on live data. This information can be used to trigger retraining of models. Both Cases A and B have capability to monitor how the model is performing in production.
